  "zh:Semiconductor Supply Chains: Why Shortages Happen and How to Build Resilience": "半导体供应链：为什么会发生短缺以及如何建立弹性",
  "zh:Please recall everything you can from the article in 3 minutes. Describe why semiconductor shortages occurred, what structural factors made supply fragile, and how visibility, flexibility, contracts, and cooperation can strengthen resilience.": "请在 3 分钟内回忆起文章中的所有内容。描述为什么会发生半导体短缺，哪些结构性因素导致供应脆弱，以及可见性、灵活性、合同和合作如何增强弹性。",
  "zh:Semiconductors power nearly every modern product, yet their global network is fragile. The 2020—22 shortage arose from synchronized disruptions: pandemic shutdowns, surging demand, logistics failures, and disasters that exposed how concentrated production had become. Fabrication is capital-intensive and slow; each chip family requires unique photomasks and multi-month cycles, making rapid adjustment impossible. Automakers' cautious contracts lost priority to high-margin electronics firms, while bottlenecks in materials and equipment spread delays worldwide. Geographic concentration in East Asia and dependence on specialized suppliers magnified vulnerability. Resilience now means mapping multi-tier dependencies, designing boards that accept alternative chips, and signing take-or-pay or pre-payment contracts that align incentives. Governments can co-fund new fabs if access remains open across industries. Inventory logic has shifted from just-in-time to risk-adjusted buffers that trade efficiency for continuity. Digital twins, AI forecasting, and blockchain tracking enhance visibility, while coordinated industrial policy—through acts such as CHIPS and joint EU programs—can prevent subsidy races. Resilient ecosystems rely on trust built before crisis: transparent data, long-term partnerships, and predictable rules. The lesson is systemic: resilience lies not in isolation but in collaboration that balances physics, finance, and politics to absorb shocks and recover quickly when the next disruption arrives.": "半导体几乎为所有现代产品提供动力，但其全球网络却很脆弱。 2020-22 年的短缺是由同步中断引起的：大流行性停工、需求激增、物流故障以及暴露生产集中程度的灾难。制造是资本密集型且缓慢的；每个芯片系列都需要独特的光掩模和数月的周期，因此无法进行快速调整。汽车制造商谨慎的合同失去了对高利润电子公司的优先权，而材料和设备的瓶颈在全球范围内蔓延。地理集中在东亚以及对专业供应商的依赖放大了脆弱性。现在的弹性意味着映射多层依赖关系、设计接受替代芯片的电路板，以及签署与激励措施相一致的照付不议或预付款合同。如果各行业的准入保持开放，政府可以共同资助新晶圆厂。库存逻辑已经从及时调整转向风险调整缓冲，以效率换取连续性。数字孪生、人工智能预测和区块链跟踪提高了可见性，而协调的产业政策（通过 CHIPS 和欧盟联合计划等行动）可以防止补贴竞赛。有弹性的生态系统依赖于危机前建立的信任：透明的数据、长期的合作伙伴关系和可预测的规则。这个教训是系统性的：韧性不在于孤立，而在于平衡物理、金融和政治的合作，以吸收冲击并在下一次破坏到来时迅速恢复。",
  "zh:- Semiconductors power modern products; 2020—22 shortage revealed fragile supply chains.\n- Pandemic disruptions: demand surges, factory shutdowns, logistics failures, material disasters.\n- Fabrication is capital-intensive with multi-month cycles; rapid adjustment impossible.\n- Automakers' modest contracts lost priority to high-margin electronics orders.\n- Geographic concentration in East Asia creates systemic vulnerability.\n- Resilience tactics: map multi-tier suppliers, design for component flexibility, use take-or-pay contracts.\n- Shift from just-in-time to risk-adjusted inventory buffers.\n- Digital twins, AI forecasting enhance visibility; policy coordination prevents subsidy races.\n- Trust-based partnerships with transparent data enable shock absorption and faster recovery.": "- 半导体为现代产品提供动力； 2020年22月，短缺暴露了供应链的脆弱。\n- 流行病造成的破坏：需求激增、工厂关闭、物流故障、重大灾难。\n- 制造是资本密集型的​​，周期长达数月；快速调整是不可能的。\n- 汽车制造商的适度合同失去了高利润电子产品订单的优先权。\n- 地理集中于东亚造成系统性脆弱性。\n- 弹性策略：映射多层供应商、设计组件灵活性、使用照付不议合同。\n- 从及时库存缓冲转向风险调整库存缓冲。\n- 数字孪生、人工智能预测增强可视性；政策协调可以防止补贴竞赛。\n- 基于信任的伙伴关系和透明的数据可以吸收冲击并更快地恢复。",
